item.title: Artillery sidewinder X1 bracket design
item.description:
Screws:
4pc. M6 x 10 hex socket
8pc. M5 x 35 hex socket
4pc. M5 x 20 hex socket
2pc. M5 x 40 hex socket
6pc. M5 Nut

2 x Al profile 2020 length 574.5mm with additional M6 threads at both ends (manually cut directly by M6 screw tap)

This is my solution for improving the Z Axis stiffness and thus the printing quality.

I used spray paint to color the profile black.
PLA Material used: Spectrum PLA matt

Material required:
Screws:
4pc. M6 x 10 hex socket
8pc. M5 x 35 hex socket
4pc. M5 x 20 hex socket
2pc. M5 x 40 hex socket
6pc. M5 Nut

2 x Al profile 2020 length 574.5mm with additional M6 threads at both ends (manually cut directly by M6 screw tap)

Others:

  • drill ø5mm for drilling 4 holes into the sidewinder housing using a printed drill jig. See above on the STL files.
  1. Print out all parts required
  2. Drill 4 holes into the sheet metal housing of the sidewinder using the drill jig
  3. Fix bottom part and upper block with M5 screws. Use counter plate inside the sidewinder housing. Tighten up all screws nuts.
  4. Mount end pieces on bottom side of the Al profile
  5. Insert both profiles to the upper blocks (see also step 7) and tighten up top M6 Screws that go into to profile
  6. Mount horizontal screws into bottom part / end pieces and temporary fix the M5 nuts on each side
  7. Losen the M5 screws that go into the Z profile
    on each side when doing step 5.
  8. lift x-axis all the way up to before tightening M5 screws on Step 7
  9. tighten up everything again.

item.title: Cartesian 3D Coordinate Axes
item.description:
These are just some simple coordinate axes. I'm the kind of person that needs to have a thing to touch and manipulate when I'm thinking quantitatively in 3 dimensions, so I find having this sort of thing helpful for doing vector coordinate transformations and that kind of thing.

I included axes labeled (x,y,z) and (u,v,w). My recommendation is that you print (x,y,z) in 100% scale, and (u,v,w) in 75% scale so that if you are imagining a coordinate transformation, the (x,y,z) system is the base coordinates and the (u,v,w) system is the primed coordinates.

item.title: Simpsons TV for 3.5 inch screen
item.description:
I modified the original Simpsons TV by buba447 to accommodate a 3.5 inch screen by Waveshare since the screen he used is no longer available. The rest of the parts, except for the potentiometer, are the same as the original build, although I included the original volume knob in the files so the original potentiometer should work as well.

I reinforced the main body so it is less flimsy, changed the speaker grill on the back, added tabs to center the 40mm speaker, and added some vents because it gets a little warm with the bigger screen (and I used a raspberry pi model A to make it easier to get audio output).

Some slight cleanup will likely be required for the parts to fit well, especially if your first layer prints too close to the bed like mine. In case you use Windows 3D Builder, I included all the parts in the 3mf file to make editing easier. The only part that needs support is the front panel under the legs.

build guide:
https://withrow.io/simpsons-tv-build-guide

Here are the parts I used different from the original build:
screen:
https://thepihut.com/products/3-5-ips-dpi-capacitive-touchscreen-display-for-raspberry-pi
screen documentation:
https://www.waveshare.com/wiki/3.5inch_DPI_LCD

potentiometer:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B071WW6VN8/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_image?ie=UTF8&psc=1

item.title: CleanRite Paint shaker (Cheap)
item.description:
This is an addon for the large brush on the cleanrite electric brush.

For this to fit you need to pull out all the hairs from the 33mm brush and attach this holder with 2 M2 self tapping screws.

This bottle holder should work with most 17ml/0,57 fl. oz. dripper bottles.

Tested it with Vallejo and Scale75 bottles. As the brush makes 10000 movements per minute an agitating ball is not stricly neccesary, but for some paints it might help.

At the moment I use the offcenter version, but the centered one might give better battery life and less stress on the moving parts.

The brush used for this project can be found here: https://cleanrite.eu/en/cleaning-brushes/multi-scrubber-starter-package-basic/

For the best price you might get it at the Action stores for about 6 euros (at least in the Netherlands)

item.title: Sovol SV01 Rear Z Brace For 1/2" Aluminum Pipes
item.description:
!!!MUST BE MIRRORED IN YOUR SLICER TO PRINT BOTH SIDES!!!

I designed this to replace the old one I had. Since the pipes sat in-line with the frame itself, the cable chain was rubbing into it constantly and it didn't give anything that much space to move around. This bolts to the side of the frame, so it achieves a lighter footprint while being just as sturdy as any other brace. If you have any issues with the parts, please let me know and I'll try my best to fix it!

P.S. You will need to remove the bearing blocks at the top of the lead screws, since the top half needs to be screwed in at that location!

Hardware needed:

1/2" Aluminum pipe, ~20" length for each side
x4 M3x10 Screws
x4 M3 Hex Nuts
x8 M5x16 Screws
x8 M5 T-Slot Nuts

Can be printed in PETG, ABS, and Nylon. PLA might not be rigid enough.

item.title: Dr. E Fat Tail Cat Tall Smartphone Stand - "Birdie"
item.description:
This is Dr. E Fat Tail Cat Tall Smartphone Stand! I printed one of those small cat smartphone stand for my daughter and she started using during breakfast. Problem is, she started putting the smartphone stand on top of a kleenex box as she wanted to view at nearer eye-height. Well, whenever we have breakfast and she is using her smartphone, it blocks the opening of kleenex box so every kleenex gets torn apart.

I realized that most smartphone stands are not ergonomically correct so I made a much taller smartphone stand so you can view youtube/movies on your smartphone more easily nearer eye level.

I made the smartphone stand so the smartphone itself angles itself slightly upwards and it's tall enough to make you more comfortable than using a small stand that sits on the bottom of the table.

Also, I traced a photo of my cat to make the model of the cat, his name is "Birdie".

Fits small smartphones and even larger smartphone like Galaxy Note 20.
